was looking to see if they had lactobac culture so you could really make your bespoke buttermilk and learned a cool trick: for baking you can fake it by just adding 1tblsp of vinegar to 8 oz of your ~1% or skim milk after churning, let set a few minutes & then use as buttermilk.
i mean if you want to be safe and all... the cultured stuff you can buy in the supermarket just adds lactobacillus. but the real deal is a genuine difference in taste.

that said, i love buttermilk. like just to drink. but if you really want to taste a difference, try traditional versus the cultured stuff you get mostly in the grocery store. if you go to indian or nepali grocery stores you can find the good stuff.

not to be even more of a dilettante, but cream in grocery stores is pasteurized. buttermilk is the fermented milk left over from making butter. so unless it was unpasteurized or you added lactococcus (which is how most buttermilk is now made), you actually have just milk.
